5.title: Consent
5.content:
Informed Consent

We are conducting this web-based study in order to investigate mental processes using bistabile images (see next page for an example). You will see an image on the screen and you will be asked to press a button according to your perception of the image.

Before participating it is important that you understand what your participation would involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully.

In order to participate, you must be 18 years or older. There are special incentives to participate in the study.

Your participation in this study is completely voluntary and you may withdraw at any time without penalty. If you choose to participate, it will take approximately 5-10 minutes of your time.

Your privacy and safety will be respected at all times. Participants will not be identified by the data collected. Please note that it will therefore not be possible to request or delete your data, as it will not be possible to identify it. Please do not enter any information that may de-anonymize yourself (such as email adresses). Contact details will be repeated on the last page, so that you can contact us for any question regarding the study.

There are none known potential consequences of participating in the study; potential risks, adverse side effects or discomfort are not to be expected. Participants do not have to answer all questions asked of them and can stop their participation at any time

Data (anonymous) will be stored for research purposes for an indefinite period of time. It is planned to provide the data openly so that other researcher may use them for subsequent research.

You are free to withdraw from the research study at any time without explanation, disadvantage or consequence. However, if you withdraw, I would reserve the right to use Material that you provide up until the point of my analysis of the data.

By clicking you confirm that you have read and understood the information provided above. If you agree to participate, please hit the Space bar.

Please press space to proceed to the instructions for this study.

6.title: Pseudonym
6.content:
Personal and study ID (optional)

If you have been asked to create a personal anonymous ID (pseudonym), please enter it below. Similarly, if have have been given an ID for this study, please enter it in the second box.

If you do not have that information, just skip the respective box.

Please press Space to continue.

7.title: Instructions
7.content:
Instructions

There will be two rounds:

1. In the first round, your task is to hold the perspective as long as possible. Don't let it flip as long as possible.

2. In the second round, your task is to flip the perspective as soon and as often as possible. Don't let the perspective remain, try to make it flip.

Each round will consist of 20 flips; once you indicated that the Necker cube has flipped 20 times, the round will be over.

In each round, your job is to hit the space key as soon as and every time when your perception of the cube changes.

It is important to remain focused and undisturbed during the whole experiment. Please make sure you direct your whole attention to the task at hand. Please disable distractions.

Please hit Space-Taste, if you are ready to start.

Please press Space to begin the experiment.

9.title: Necker Loop - hold as long as possible

10.title: Necker Cube
10.content:
The "Necker Cube" - main research object of this study

Below you can seee the wire-frame "Necker Cube" (upper panel). If you look ath the cube long enough, it will seem to "flip" between patterns. These two patterns are depicted in the lower panel.

Test it: Concentrate on the cube (upper panel) until your perception flips.

Your task will be to concentrate on the cube, hitting the space key each time and as soon as your perception flips.

It does not matter whether it flips from this to that perception, or from that to this perception. It does not matter how long it takes until it flips. Just hit the space bar whenever a flip occurs.

Please press space to proceed to the instructions for this study.

metadata.title: Attention span study using the Necker Cube bistabile image
metadata.description:
This study investigates attentional processes using a well-known bistabile image paradigm. Precisely, participants watch the Necker cube, a simple wire frame cube. The necker cube can be perceived in one of two perspectives. After a couple of seconds, the perspective "flips" from one perspective to the other. This flip or change in perception cannot (readily) suspended by will, although there is some variation in the inter-flip interval. For instance, the flip span has be associated with the temporal expansion of the working memory (cf. Sauer et al., 2012).

Literature
